Thermal gravimetric analysis (TGA) of compounds 1–4 were investigated under the flowing nitrogen atmosphere (
). Unusually, they exhibit two kinds of thermal behavior. The TG curves of 1 and 2 only show one platform from room temperature to 370 °C, then the ligand decomposition makes the whole framework totally collapse. In comparison, there are two obvious platforms in the TG plots of 3 and 4. For 3, The first weight loss of 24% from 280 to ca. 330 °C corresponds to the full liberation of e-urea molecules (calcd: 23.6%), and the remaining framework [Zn(ntd)]n shows no weight loss up to ca. 400 °C. The compared powder X-ray diffraction patterns further confirm that the framework [Zn(ntd)]n does not change at 300 °C, but it shifts to an unknown phase after full removal of the e-urea ligands at 350 °C (
). The total solvent-accessible volume of 3 is estimated to be 34.9% using the PLATON program . The TGA curve of 4 is similar to that of 3, but 4 has higher thermal stability than 3. As demonstrated by the powder X-ray diffraction patterns, the framework of 4 does not change at 350 °C.

