To explore the potential photoluminescence sensing properties of 1, the fine grinding sample of 1 (3mg) was dispersed in 3mL of various solvents (EtOH, MeCN, DMF, CH2Cl2, THF, acetone, H2O, toluene (TO), benzene (BZ), nitrobenzene(NB)) sonicated for 30min and the emission was observed. The fluorescence intensities are mainly dependent on the solvent molecules, which present different fluorescence quenching degree (
). Among the chosen solvents, the severe quenching of fluorescence intensity was observed in NB, indicating that 1 has a selective response to NB. The mechanism of fluorescence quenching might be attributed to the photoinduced electron transfer from an excited MOF to the highly electron deficient NB adsorbed on the surface of 1
. The fluorescence quenching of 1 is similar to that reported for many other fluorescent MOFs in order to account for their highly selective sensing behavior towards NB .

