We herein utilize 4,4′-(hexafluoroisopropylidene)diphthalic acid (H4L) for the construction of cluster-based Ln-MOF from the following reasons: 1) besides versatile coordination modes generated by multicarboxylate groups, H4L has three configurations (
) caused by the rotation of CC bonds between the C(CF3)2 group and two end benzene rings , which can satisfy the complex coordination geometry of lanthanide center; 2) the adjacent arrangement of the carboxylate groups on each benzene ring can allow the neighboring carboxylate groups to bind different lanthanide centers, generating metal-carboxylate cluster; 3) H4L has recently been utilized to construct MOFs with transition metal ions Mn2+, Ni2+, Cu2+, Zn2+ and Cd2+, respectively, which display well luminescent, magnetic and sorptive properties , however, Ln-MOF containing H4L is still unexplored. In our latest work, a microporous Cd-MOF has been assembled with H4L, in which the unique structural character of H4L makes the MOF have hydrophilic/hydrophobic channels and excellent sorption capacity for CO2
. Ongoing with our interest in structural and functional investigations of metal multicarboxylate frameworks, a new dinuclear- and tetranuclear-based terbium framework [Tb4L3(H2O)9]·7H2O (1) with L4− as linkers has been synthesized.

AbstractThree cobalt(II) complexes with the formulas: {H[CoL3]·4.17MeOH·13.3H2O}
